Also amazing was that Shaun was able to survive in the wild for so long.

'Usually they get cast and can't get up, or they get fly-struck or the hot weather gets to them,' Mr Hazell said.

Shaun's haircut today revealed a trembling, spindly animal under his mass of hair.

It must have been a shock to the animal, as his fleece has become one of the heaviest ever sheared from a single sheep.

But it does not beat the world record, which is held by a New Zealander named Shrek. 

The merino shot to international fame in 2004 after he avoided being caught and shorn for six years. Merinos are normally shorn annually, but Shrek apparently hid in caves, avoiding muster.

His fleece weighed an astonishing 27kg, and he was even taken to meet New Zealand's Prime Minister.

